  sisobus
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Output:  code flows like wind

  How it flows
  ------------
  This is a wind demo, not a labyrinth. The IP doesn't walk the
  grid — it gusts.

  Row 0 builds the message in reverse-byte order so 'c' lands on
  top of the stack, then `v` redirects the IP south. On the next
  tick, `≫` raises its speed to 2.

  From there on, the IP travels at speed 2. Each tick it advances
  TWO cells in its current direction; only the destination cell
  decodes (SPEC §3.7). The first speed-2 step takes it from
  (22, 1) past the intermediate cell at (22, 2) and lands on
  (22, 3), where `↘` flips the direction to south-east. After
  that, every tick advances (+2, +2) — and the message has been
  laid out so that the IP lands on a fresh `,` print cell every
  single time:

    tick   landing  speed   action
    ----   -------- -----   ----------------------
     n     (22, 1)    1     ≫: speed → 2
     n+1   (22, 3)    2     ↘: dir → SE
     n+2   (24, 5)    2     ,: print 'c'
     n+3   (26, 7)    2     ,: print 'o'
     n+4   (28, 9)    2     ,: print 'd'
            ...
     n+21  (62, 43)   2     ,: print 'd' (last)
     n+22  (64, 45)   2     @: halt

  The cells the IP flies over — every other cell along the
  cascade — are `↗` (NE) glyphs. They look like crosswinds
  blowing back up against the SE flow. The IP never decodes
  them, so they're aesthetically free: pure visual texture for
  the human reader.

  But they aren't decoration only. They are the program's only
  defense against a slower IP. Without `≫`, a speed-1 traversal
  steps onto the very first `↗` and gets flung up-right into the
  empty far field of the grid, where it drifts forever. So the
  message reaches stdout if and only if the wind is strong
  enough to skip the `↗` rip currents.

  In other words: this isn't 20 print operations dressed up in
  diagonal art. It's a layout that's structurally untraversable
  at the wrong speed, and exactly traversable at speed 2 — and
  the 20-cell print pattern that emerges out of that traversal
  happens to spell "code flows like wind".

  Things to notice
  ----------------
  - The whole program lives on one diagonal. Trace the source
    top-down, left-to-right, and each row's single character
    drifts one column further east. That's the IP's actual
    trajectory drawn into the file.

  - Step through it under `windy debug examples/anthem.wnd` and
    watch the position counter walk (+2, +2) per tick across
    rows 3 → 5 → 7 → ... → 45. The state panel's `speed` row
    will read 2 the entire way.
